# Room 5 Lynux Fundamentals Part 2 

## Task 1 Remote access:

- Deployed a Linux machine and the TryHackMe AttackBox.
- Connected via ssh tryhackme@MACHINE_IP.

---

## Task 2 Flags and manuals:

- Extended command functionality with flags (ls -a, ls -l).
- Consulted documentation using --help and man.

---

## task 3 Filesystem interaction:

- Created files (touch) and directories (mkdir).
- Deleted files (rm) and directories (rm -R).
- Copied files (cp) and moved/renamed files (mv).
- Verified file type with file.

---

## Task 4 Permissions and users:

- Listed permissions with ls -lh.
- Analyzed symbolic (rwxrwxrwx) and numeric formats (777, 755, 644).
- Switched users with su user2 and su -l user2.
- Applied permissions using chmod.

---

## task 5 Common root directories:

- /etc: system configuration files (e.g., sudoers, passwd, shadow).
- /var: variable data such as logs (/var/log).
- /root: home directory of the root user.
- /tmp: temporary storage, cleared on reboot, writable by all users.

---

## Tools Used

- Protocols and access: SSH (Secure Shell), TryHackMe AttackBox (Ubuntu)
- Core commands: ls, cd, man, touch, mkdir, rm, cp, mv, file, chmod, su
- Root directories: /etc, /var, /root, /tmp

## Findings

- SSH enables secure remote command execution.
- Flags and manuals expand and document command behavior.
- File operations (touch, mkdir, rm, cp, mv) are essential for system administration.
- Permissions control access and must be configured with least privilege.
- Root directories contain critical information that requires protection and monitoring.

## Mitigation / Best Practices

- Always use SSH with secure credentials and encryption.
- Regularly consult man and --help to understand command options.
- Apply minimal necessary permissions with chmod to reduce security risks.
- Monitor /var/log for anomalies and protect sensitive files in /etc.
- Restrict /root access to authorized administrators only.
- Use /tmp cautiously in pentesting, avoiding insecure or persistent files.

